title: For Sale:  Manurhin P1 (P38)
location: Central Rhode Island, Rhode Island, United States
postcontent: This P1 Manurhin "Pistolet" is in very good condition with some normal wear. Chambered in 9mm Luger, it comes with 2 original magazines and the original (worn) holster stamped with "Wunderlich, Berlin 1963". Shoots great and is a historical piece. Must use my FFL for transfer $25 to him.It is a P38 in sheeps clothing if you will. It was made for the West Berlin Polizei (Police) in 1963. It was manufactured by Walther/Ulm but stamped and assembled by Manurhin in Bourzwiller/France. Beacause of post WWII/Cold War laws, West Berlin Police were not allowed to purchase "German" weapons, hence the "diversion" via Manurhin. It carrys the West/Berlin police stamp (a "rosette") on the lhs of the triggerguard. It also carrys another stamp ("crossed cannons") on the rhs of the slide. The meaning of that stamp is unknown - maybe Portuguese? This P1 was sold in between 1983 and 1987 on the commercial market.

title: For Sale:  BEWARE!!!!
postcontent: I've been contacted twice lately by scammers wanting to buy my rifle. They went to great lengths too. Mailed me a phoney check from Maryland via Priority Mail. (But said they resided in Florida) On a credit union in Pennsylvania. The check looked real, but was bogus. (My bank called the credit union) They started texting me from Minnesota. Offered me an extra $100 to hold the rifle for them. Said their FFL would come pick the gun up for them. The check was for much more than the agreed price, so I could pay their FFL for his trouble. Then wanted me to send the balance via Western Union to a woman in Washington State. (Their FFl was now a woman) The Washington Zip Code was actually in Mexico. They wanted me to wire the money via the 10 min. transfer process. (they would cover the fee) They then panicked when I told them I had used the proper zip code for the city in Washington. and had lost the receipt with the code needed to pick up the funds from Western Union, but that they could just show their ID. ( I was having a little fun at this point) Finally, I confessed that I was screwing with them, we exchanged a few "well wishs" which ended with an implied threat of death in my sleep. This time they were in Alabama, but couldn't do a FTF transfer. Their inital contact e-mail was virtually identical to the first. I knew who I was dealing with this time, so we only exchanged a few "pleasantries"    Follow Armslists advice and do Face to Face transfers of weapons only.    Most folks are good, but there are some real crooks out there these days.    I've sent some parts and other things as far west as California before.    But heck, I know I can trust me.    Use your common sense, if it seems too good to be true, it probably is.    Happy 4th of July!
